---
# ==============================================================================
# .clang-tidy
# ==============================================================================
# This configuration file establishes rigorous static analysis rules for 
# safety-critical embedded C development. It focuses on finding bugs, preventing
# undefined behavior, and enforcing secure coding standards (CERT, MISRA) while
# carefully tuning out false positives inherent to low-level hardware interaction.
# ==============================================================================

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Checks Configuration
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# -*: Disables all default checks so we can explicitly opt-in to what we need.
# bugprone-*: Detects code constructs that are likely to be bugs or cause unexpected behavior.
# cert-*: Enforces SEI CERT C Coding Standard rules for secure coding.
# performance-*: Identifies suboptimal code constructs.
# readability-*: Enforces readability rules.
# misc-*: Miscellaneous checks, often catching undefined behavior.
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Checks: >
  -*,
  bugprone-*,
  cert-*,
  performance-*,
  misc-*,
  readability-*,
  clang-analyzer-*,
  concurrency-*,
  portability-*,
  -readability-magic-numbers,
  -bugprone-easily-swappable-parameters,
  -bugprone-branch-clone

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Justifications for Disabled Checks (The "Why")
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# -readability-magic-numbers:
#   Hardware register addresses (e.g., 0x40021000) and bitmasks (e.g., 1 << 5) are
#   inherently "magic numbers". While macros/constants should be used, enabling this
#   check globally creates an unmanageable amount of noise in HAL (Hardware Abstraction
#   Layer) code. We disable it to prevent analysis fatigue.
#
# -bugprone-easily-swappable-parameters:
#   In embedded APIs, it is very common to have sequential parameters of the same type 
#   (e.g., x, y coordinates or row, col indices). While technically a risk, flagging 
#   all instances causes massive friction in graphics or matrix-based drivers.
#
# -bugprone-branch-clone:
#   Sometimes explicit and symmetric branch logic is required for state machines or 
#   timing reasons (e.g., ensuring identical execution paths for secure operations),
#   making branch clone checks falsely report necessary symmetry.

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CheckOptions Configuration
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
CheckOptions:
  # Enforce rigorous limits on cognitive complexity. 
  # Functions that exceed this complexity are statistically more likely to contain
  # bugs and are harder to test comprehensively (violates structural coverage goals).
  - key:             readability-function-cognitive-complexity.Threshold
    value:           '15'
  
  # Ensure all variables are initialized before use, a critical safety requirement.
  - key:             bugprone-unhandled-exception-at-new.Disabled
    value:           'true'

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Severe Violation Enforcement
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Treat specific severe violations as errors that break the build.
# We ensure that CERT and Bugprone rules are never bypassed.
WarningsAsErrors: >
  bugprone-*,
  cert-*,
  clang-analyzer-core.*,
  misc-static-assert

HeaderFilterRegex: '^src/.*'
FormatStyle:     'file'
...
